perience of Jews, Poles, Greeks, and others, notably in the United States. Yet, little is known about the paths of mass migration across “green borders” via European railway stations and ports to destinations in other continents. Ellis Island, literally a point of passage into America, has a much higher symbolic significance than the often inconspicuous departure stations, makeshift facilities for migrant masses at European railway stations and port cities, and former control posts along borders that were redrawn several times during the twentieth century. This volume focuses on the journeys of Jews from Eastern Europe through Germany, Britain, and Scandinavia between 1880 and 1914. The authors investigate various aspects of transmigration including medical controls, travel conditions, and the role of the steamship lines; and also review the rise of migration restrictions around the globe in the decades before 1914.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aJewszEuropexHistoryy19th century. 0aJewszEuropexSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aJewszEurope, EasternxMigrations. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aJewish Studies, History (General), Refugee and Migration Studies.1 aBrinkmann, Tobias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrinkmann, Tobias, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarlsson, Carl Henrik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEilers, Nicole Kvale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeeling, Drew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKushner, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLüthi, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSebak, Per Kristian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g